======================================================================
PART 6: RESONANCE CONDITION — WHEN DOES THE CASCADE AMPLIFY?
======================================================================

The Morgan-Voyce transfer at x=1 has tr(T_B) = 3 > 2.
This puts us in the GAP regime of the associated Schrödinger operator!

In the band: |tr| ≤ 2 → oscillatory (Bloch waves)
In the gap: |tr| > 2 → exponential growth (evanescent waves)

For tournament H-maximization:
  x = 1 → tr = 3 → GAP → exponential growth → F_p ~ φ^p
  x = 0 → tr = 2 → BAND EDGE → linear growth → B_m(0) = 1
  x = -1 → tr = 1 → BAND → oscillatory → B_m(-1) ∈ {0,±1}

THE RESONANCE CASCADE:

  Level m=1: B_1(1) = 2 = F_3
  Level m=2: B_2(1) = 5 = F_5 (amplified by 2.5×)
  Level m=3: B_3(1) = 13 = F_7 (amplified by 2.6×)
  Level m=4: B_4(1) = 34 = F_9 (amplified by 2.615×)
  Level m=5: B_5(1) = 89 = F_11 (amplified by 2.6176×)
  ...
  Level m→∞: amplification → φ² = 2.618034

Each level amplifies by a factor converging to φ².
This is the Fibonacci resonance cascade!

======================================================================
PART 7: SCHRÖDINGER OPERATOR ANALOGY
======================================================================

Schrödinger analogy:
  Hamiltonian: H_S = -Δ + V (1D discrete Laplacian + potential)
  Transfer matrix: T = [[E-V, -1], [1, 0]]

  Morgan-Voyce: T_B = [[2+x, -1], [1, 0]]
  ⟹ E - V = 2 + x

  At x = 1 (Fibonacci): E - V = 3, in the GAP
  At x = 0 (trivial): E - V = 2, at the BAND EDGE
  At x = -1 (period-6): E - V = 1, in the BAND

  DEEP INSIGHT: The parameter x controls whether the cascade
  AMPLIFIES (x > 0, gap) or OSCILLATES (x < 0, band).
  Fibonacci numbers arise precisely because x = 1 puts us
  in the gap where exponential growth occurs!

